HEADWORD: Lygodium
<hw>Ly*go"di*um</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <?/
flexible; <?/ a willow twig + <grk>e'i^dos</grk> form.]</ety>
<fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A genus of ferns with twining or climbing fronds,
bearing stalked and variously-lobed divisions in pairs.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <spn>Lygodium palmatum</spn>, much prized for indoor
ornament, inhabits shaded and moist grassy places, from Massachusetts to
Virginia and Kentucky, and sparingly southwards.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lygus</ent>⟦br⟧
